      <introduction>
        <p>
      Consider the series
      <me>
        \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{k^2}
      </me>.
    </p>
        <p>
      While it is physically impossible to add an infinite collection of numbers,
      we can, of course, add any finite collection of them.
      In what follows,
      we investigate how understanding how to find the <m>n</m>th partial sum
      (that is, the sum of the first <m>n</m> terms)
      enables us to make sense of the infinite sum.

      </p>
      </introduction>
